ne?=E2=80=94made a comment about the advisor=E2=80=99s challenging personal=
ity and inquired, =E2=80=9CWhy do you work with that person?=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=
</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0=
;margin-bottom:0px;">Unperturbed, the collector responded that, while he wa=
s fully aware of the
advisor=E2=80=99s limitations, he needed someone who did a lot of business =
with the Zwirners, Hausers, and Gagosians of the world to get him to the he=
ad of the line. Indeed, he was acknowledging a central truth of this part o=
f the business: Access is the currency of the primary market. By zealously =
developing that access, art advisors have been able to generate value for t=
hemselves and for the galleries. (Who do you think keeps collectors from go=
ing rogue and flipping in-demand works? The advisors, who
need to protect their gallery relationships.)=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0=
;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Aft=
er all, a good advisor can make a <em>great</em> deal of money working for =
only a few committed clients who transact at the top of the market=E2=80=94=
they get paid, at least in part, based on the volume of their transactions.=
 And like the family-office industry, which has grown up to service the nee=
ds and whims of the ultra-wealthy, art advisors have emerged
to handle the unique challenges of navigating an individual=E2=80=99s entr=
=C3=A9e into collecting or managing ever-larger collections. But for a numb=
er of reasons=E2=80=94from competition over deals that often discourages tr=
ansparency and cooperation, to the conflicts of interest that would inevita=
bly arise within more expansive firms=E2=80=94there have been no market for=
ces incentivizing independent advisors to band together to create a large-s=
cale advisory firm that would mirror the consolidation of the auction and
gallery businesses. As a result, a mega advisory has yet to emerge.=C2=A0</=
p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;m=
argin-bottom:0px;">That=E2=80=99s not to say firms aren=E2=80=99t growing. =
<strong>Sandy Heller</strong>, perhaps the premier art advisor of his time,=
 has added as partners <strong>Jean-Olivier Despr=C3=A9s</strong> in Paris =
and <strong>Etsuko Nakajima</strong> in Tokyo. <strong>Jussi Pylkk=C3=A4nen=
</strong> recently opened his own advisory firm. When <strong>Wentworth
Beaumont</strong> and <strong>Hugo Nathan</strong> joined forces in 2014, t=
heir goal was to build a best-in-class organization that was more than a li=
festyle business for themselves and could bring a level of professionalism =
to art advising, which often seems more like a cottage industry. To a degre=
e, they=E2=80=99ve succeeded, but it has taken them a decade to build trust=
 with both clients and dealers. And in order to grow, they=E2=80=99ve had t=
o train their own talent.=C2=A0=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;
margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">Earlier this week, whe=
n I spoke to the team at Beaumont Nathan about the promotion of three longt=
ime employees to equity partners, it seemed like a good time to ask the pos=
sibly awkward, but unavoidable, question: Why haven=E2=80=99t we seen the e=
mergence of a large global advisory firm to match those global galleries an=
d auction houses? After all, the art industry behaves like any other: There=
 is a value chain as an object goes from creator to
consumer, and the expansion of any one link should have a ripple effect, th=
ereby enhancing the others. Why has the art advisor business been immune?=
=C2=A0</p></div>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
