28.799999999999997px;"><strong>The AAP Memory</strong></h3>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
<table width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" role=
=3D"presentation" style=3D"mso-table-lspace:0pt;mso-table-rspace:0pt;word-b=
reak:break-word;"><tbody><tr><td class=3D"r" style=3D"padding-bottom:32px;"=
><div style=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;Inter&#39;,&#39=
;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;line-height:1=
50%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"margin:0;margi=
n-bottom:0px;">The first real attempt to build a large-scale advisory busin=
ess took place in
2016, at Sotheby=E2=80=99s, when the auction house paid $85 million to acqu=
ire Art Agency, Partners. The deal was essentially an acquihire of the firm=
=E2=80=99s three partners, with Sotheby=E2=80=99s installing <strong>Amy Ca=
ppellazzo</strong> as head of the fine art division, giving <strong>Adam Ch=
inn</strong> the role of chief operating officer, and leaving <strong>Allan=
 Schwartzman</strong> to run the AAP team inside the corporation. It seemed=
 like a natural expansion of what an auction house ought to provide its
clients=E2=80=94Sotheby=E2=80=99s seemed to be morphing into an analog of t=
he big Wall Street banks, with a trading floor (the auction room), an inves=
tment bank providing liquidity options (Sotheby=E2=80=99s Financial Service=
s), and, now, a private bank offering advisory services (AAP).</p><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bott=
om:0px;">But for AAP to grow, it needed to build a roster of younger adviso=
rs who could benefit from Schwartzman=E2=80=99s reputation and visibility t=
o eventually
establish their own client bases. Strategically, at least, that sounds easy=
 enough, but it=E2=80=99s very hard to put into practice. Personalities don=
=E2=80=99t always align, and short-term priorities can get in the way of lo=
ng-term growth. In the end, Sotheby=E2=80=99s just didn=E2=80=99t have a de=
ep enough management bench to figure out a way to build AAP. By the time <s=
trong>Patrick Drahi </strong>bought the company in 2019, the art advisory b=
usiness didn=E2=80=99t fit with Drahi=E2=80=99s vision of Sotheby=E2=80=99s=
 as a luxury retailer burnished
by the auction house=E2=80=99s reputation. Soon after the change in ownersh=
ip, Schwartzman left.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p=
><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">In my conversations with the folk=
s at Beaumont Nathan, the partners all felt strongly that their ability to =
grow beyond the founders=E2=80=9460 percent of the deals are now done by ad=
visors who don=E2=80=99t have their names on the door=E2=80=94was a combina=
tion of information-sharing across the firm and a conscious program of ment=
orship. In
other words: good management. The Beaumont Nathan leadership team recognize=
d that growth depended on developing more advisors, rather than trying to h=
ire advisors from outside, or ex-auction house personnel with a similar ski=
ll set. (As those who have worked inside auction houses and galleries have =
noted, information-sharing is rare among people who stand to earn commissio=
ns from sales.)</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">The other
challenge to scaling an advisory business relates to how advisors are compe=
nsated: typically via retainer, a commission on sales, or a flat fee for a =
particular project. Smart clients (or smart advisors) prefer a hybrid model=
 that combines a retainer with commissions=E2=80=94keeping them close but a=
lso incentivizing them in success. Some have suggested that a smarter model=
 would provide different commission rates for, say, finding a buyer for a w=
ork (which <em>really</em> adds value), and, say, managing
a relationship with an auction house. And of course, there=E2=80=99s also a=
 commission on the buy side, which doesn=E2=80=99t necessarily align the cl=
ient=E2=80=99s interest with the advisor=E2=80=99s.</p><p style=3D"margin:0=
;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Tha=
t=E2=80=99s only the beginning of the potential conflicts inherent in the a=
dvisory business. If you think a big advisory firm makes sense because of i=
ts greater reach=E2=80=94more clients means more market insight, including =
who has which works in
their collection=E2=80=94you have to manage who is representing whose inter=
ests if you want to act as a brokerage. (The big appraisal firms keep their=
 appraisers, brokers, and art advisors siloed.) There are also some advisor=
y firms that buy and hold art that they believe clients will want someday. =
Do they disclose to the eventual buyer, if it is a client of theirs, that t=
he work comes from their own holdings? They should.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">To
cover the overhead costs of a sufficiently large advisory firm, one has to =
have enough clients willing to pay a retainer. This actually argues for adv=
isory firms to be part of larger entities, like auction houses, because the=
y can carry the overhead and allow the advisors to focus on their work. Unf=
ortunately, a very successful advisor will quickly want to strike out on th=
eir own to keep more of the upside. It=E2=80=99s a fissiparous business, th=
is advising thing.=C2=A0</p></div>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
